[11] New Zealand (Canterbury)
Date: Wed 1 Apr 2015
Source: NZ Doctor [edited]
http://www.nzdoctor.co.nz/news/2015/april-2015/01/the-case-of-the-measles-that-wasn%E2%80%99t.aspx


The case of the measles that wasn't
-----------------------------------
Two cases of measles in Canterbury have been de-notified after public health staff realised the 2 cases were actually illnesses mimicking measles. Canterbury medical officer of health Alistair Humphrey told New Zealand Doctor the 2 cases turned out to be cases of enterovirus [infection] which was subsequently found to be circulating in the community. Symptoms included rash, fever and diarrhoea. The 2 cases of preschoolers were confirmed last month but Dr Humphrey says the lab tests were "weakly positive", giving an equivocal result.Both children were up to date with their immunisations, having had at least one dose of the MMR vaccine.

"Further lab tests combined with no identified source nor spread, other viruses known to be circulating which mimic measles and the cases' clinical picture, makes health authorities confident the cases were not measles," a media release from the Canterbury DHB says.

But Dr Humphrey says the public health unit was right to act on the information provided and he reminded GPs to always notify the public health authority of any suspicions of measles. He says de-notifying the cases was important from a New Zealand perspective because it means the country has been measles free for 6 months.

[Byline: Ruth Brown]

